apter 11 The Impact of the German Federal Constitutional Court on the Consolidation and Quality of Democracy -- tChapter 12 Constitutional Courts in Changing Political Systems -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConstitutional litigation in general attracts two distinct types of conflict: disputes of a highly politicized or culturally controversial nature and requests from citizens claiming a violation of a fundamental constitutional right. The side-by-side comparison between the U.S. Supreme Court and the German Federal Constitutional Court provides a novel socio-legal approach in studying constitutional litigation, focusing on conditions of mobilisation, decision-making and implementation. This updated and revised second edition includes a number of new contributions on the political status of the courts in their democratic political cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aConstitutional courts. 0aJudicial review. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh1 aBaum, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlankenburg, Erhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGawron, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGawron, Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeun, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Timothy R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKagan, Robert A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKneip, Sascha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKranenpohl, Uwe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLietzmann, Hans J., econtributor.